      },
      "source": [
        "# Data\n",
        "\n",
        "Conceived as being composed of symbols or signs, representing stimuli or signals, that are \"of no use until ... in a usable (that is, relevant) form\" (Rowley 2007)\n",
        "- (Fact) Raw facts or observations\n",
        "- (Stimuli) One or more kinds of energy waves or particles (light, heat, sound, force, electromagnetic) selected by a conscious organism or intelligent agent on the basis of a preexisting frame or inferential mechanism in the organism or agent\"\n",
        "- (Symbol) A property of an object, an event or of their environment\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "b3b39266-eb68-4bca-8272-46b7b117fac5",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "b3b39266-eb68-4bca-8272-46b7b117fac5"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Information\n",
        "\n",
        "Data that are endowed with meaning and purpose (Rowley 2007)\n",
        "\n",
        "- Structural vs Functional Information\n",
        "- Symbolic vs Subjective Information\n",
        "    - \"the meaning of statements as they are intended by the speaker/writer and understood/misunderstood by the listener/reader\"\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "9c02a069-c3ac-4c0a-8387-6852780db934",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9c02a069-c3ac-4c0a-8387-6852780db934"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Knowledge\n",
        "\n",
        "\"Knowledge is a fluid mix of framed experience, values, contextual information, expert insight and grounded intuition that provides an environment and framework for evaluating and incorporating new experiences and information. It originates and is applied in the minds of knowers. In organizations it often becomes embedded not only in documents and repositories but also in organizational routines, processes, practices and norms.\" (Wallace 2007)\n",
        "\n",
        "- (Process) synthesis of multiple sources of information over time\n",
        "- (Procedure) perception, skills, training, common sense and experience\n",
        "- (Proposition) \"belief structuring\" and \"internalization with reference to cognitive frameworks\" (Rowley 2007)\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "eba256f2-898f-4d50-ad68-09f927e24af8",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "eba256f2-898f-4d50-ad68-09f927e24af8"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Bigger Picture - from Data to Knowledge\n",
        "It is more useful to relate to the data, information, and knowledge as sets of signs rather than as meaning and its building blocks (Zins, 2009)\n",
        "\n",
        "Data Scientists are Data Detectives!\n",
        "- Data are clues (Data)\n",
        "- Data pieced together are stories (Information)\n",
        "- Combined data and context provide informed guesses about the truth (Knowledge)\n",
        "\n",
        "How do we move from data to knowledge (or even wisdom)?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "16962323-e9b7-42a2-8a4c-3f5a625d4d46",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "16962323-e9b7-42a2-8a4c-3f5a625d4d46"
      },
      "source": [
        "# \"Inference to the Best Explanation” method [Bartelborth, 2017]\n",
        "\n",
        "- Observation: Start by observing phenomena. This is your raw data. (in the detectives picture: gather clues)\n",
        "- Hypothesis Formulation: Develop potential hypotheses that might explain the observed data.\n",
        "- Refinement: Some theories might not fit the facts. So, they’re discarded.\n",
        "- Comparison: Which of our remaining theories best explains the data?\n",
        "- Selection: Choose the hypothesis (or hypotheses) that offers the most plausible and comprehensive explanation in line with other established knowledge."
      ]
    },
